This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of super resolution, which is a common task in computer vision. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel approach that combines segmentation-priors and feature attentions, which are commonly used techniques in computer vision. 

The paper also involves the use of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), which are a popular deep learning technique used for image generation and manipulation. This makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as well. 

The paper also involves the use of prior knowledge and attention mechanisms, which are commonly used in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) research. 

The proposed Residual-in-Residual Sparse Block (RRSB) architecture involves the use of sparse connections, which are commonly used in Graph Theory (cs.GR) research. 

Finally, the paper involves the use of various image datasets, which makes it likely to belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as well.
